One year ago today I lost a piece of my heart when I said goodbye to my sweet mom. Even though I had been taking care of her for the past 10 years she was my safe place, my rock, my person. Dementia didn’t dim the love or cloud our connection. The first video is just two weeks before she died and she never stopped telling us she loved us. Looking at the next pictures makes me miss how we would wrap our arms around each other. So much love. I’m so grateful that I was holding her hand until she took her last breath. I miss you so much mom, always and forever. 🌻

Did you know? April is National Stress Awareness Month! And according to the National Institute of Health, the goal is to “raise awareness of the negative impact of stress. There is no single definition for stress, but the most common explanation is physical, mental, or emotional strain or tension. While not all stress is bad, long-term stress can have harmful impacts on physical and mental health.”
Let’s stress less! How do you chill? Do you meditate? Exercise? Cook? Garden? Post a picture that we can share on #todayinla @nbcla @adriannbcla @belennbcla @robin_winston_tv @holly.hannula @stephanieolmo

Heading back to LA after a sad but beautiful trip home to Denver to say goodby to my sweet Aunt Rosie. She was my last living aunt on my Mom’s side. Her little sister. I was so lucky to get one last blessing from her last year when we buried my beautiful mom. I can’t believe an entire generation is gone. If you swipe you’ll see my mom and her  sisters and brother with baby Olivia. I loved growing up with so many aunties and uncles and now they are all gone. But I will hold their memories and their life lessons in my heart. This trip I also finally got to see my Mom and Dad’s engraved headstone. To be honest, there was something so final about it being at their gravesite that hit me like a crushing wave. I have shared my grief with you and you have shared yours. In fact, one of you sent me this beautiful saying that I am reposting because I feel it in my heart too. The price of love. I am so grateful to have loved so deeply that my heart aches. And finally if you keep swiping one beautiful Colorado sunset.🌻 I can’t wait to see you soon on #TodayinLA @nbcla with @adriannbcla @belennbcla @robin_winston_tv 🌻
P.S. I’m sorry that 2nd picture cut off my mom and my Auntie Dela. But that’s my Auntie Rosie and handsome Uncle Melvin. RIP

I’ve worried and wondered how to share this. But I don’t know any other way to get through the most important moments in my life other than to be as open and as honest as I can be. You’ve been with me every step of the way…happiness, sorrows and everything in between. This time I’m sharing my journey as a loving, supportive and admittedly scared wife. Doctors have found a tumor on my husband’s kidney. All indications are that it is cancer so tomorrow he is having surgery. Best case scenario they take out the tumor and a portion of his kidney. Worst case scenario they have to take the entire kidney. The good news is we believe we caught this early. He has a team of doctors at USC Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center that are the best of the best. He’s in good hands and for that I’m grateful because he’s my love, my life and I need him by my side. So I’ll be taking a couple days off the air. I know, as always, your heart is with me and my family and I can already feel your warm wishes. I’m sharing this with you so I can remind you to take your health seriously. If you haven’t seen your doctor in a while, please…do it. If you missed an appointment, reschedule. Do it for those you love and for those who love you.
🌻
Lynette

How do I begin to say how grateful we are? My husband’s surgery went very well. The surgeons were able to get the tumor out and save at least 75 percent of his kidney. 🙏🏽 We didn’t know how this day would end. We were all scared. Finally, tonight I saw the relief on my brave husband’s face and the tears that welled up in my beautiful daughter’s eyes, because we know how lucky and blessed we are. But there is something else I’m counting as a blessing and that is all of you who reached out with love, prayers and kindness. I’ll never be able to respond to the thousands of messages we’ve received today. But my heart is so full. Thank you for once again being there for me and my family when we needed you the most. 🌻

P.S. This is one of the first pictures David and I took when we met in Guadalajara back in 1993. I was living in Denver and he was living in LA. See that guy in the background with a Lakers jacket? It was definitely a sign that we were destined for a beautiful life in the City of Angels. 🤍

Breathe. That’s what I’ve been telling myself at every turn. First when my husband’s doctor said the word tumor. And then cancer. Surgery. Internal Bleeding. Breathe…today we got the pathology results confirming David’s tumor was kidney cancer. The margins are clear which means they believe they got it all out. Breathe. This is the best news we could get. They were able to save 75-80 percent of his kidney. We will forever be grateful to our rock star world renown surgeon @inderbirgillmd and his amazing team @uscurology and @keckmedicineusc David is now home letting me boss him around and coddle him so he can recover and get stronger. Many of you have asked what his symptoms were. And it’s part of why I wanted to share this experience with you. Maybe it will help, even if it’s just one person. A kidney stone may have actually saved my husband. Most kidney tumors don’t cause symptoms until they are much more advanced and dangerous. In fact, they’re usually spotted by chance while scanning or testing for something else. And that was the case with my husband. Because he has a history of kidney stones, when he started seeing blood in his urine we thought it was yet another pesky, excruciatingly painful kidney stone. When they scanned him for that, they spotted the tumor. That’s why we caught it early. So many of you have shared your own cancer stories of survival, loss and heartache. I’ve cried reading some of your comments. I know how fortunate we are in this moment and I can’t stop thinking about those whose stories ended differently. We are strangers sharing our lives and lessons in hopes of making a difference. So once again I beg you to take your health seriously. If you’ve been putting off seeing your doctor. Please, do it. If you think that pain in your back is stress maybe it is or maybe it’s kidney cancer. That is also one of the signs. Are you tired? Of course, we’re all tired but that can also be a sign something is wrong.  I know I sound paranoid. I’m sorry. I just want you to be healthy and happy and here. Breathe. Lynette. Breathe🌻
PS Don’t let anything stop you from kissing the one you love. Even your noses! *see pic above. 🥰

Dear friends and family,
If you know me, you know I lead with my heart. And so it is with a heart full of love that I am inviting you to join me in the Walk to End Alzheimer’s at LA Live Saturday morning October 28th. I am co-emceeing the event on behalf of NBC4. But I will be holding on tight to the memory of my beautiful mother Viola Romero who we lost almost 2 years ago. So many of you have reached out to me to share your stories of grief and loss and so I will carry you in my heart as well. I hope you’ll join me. 💜
Follow the link in my bio and it will take you to my personal Alzheimer’s Walk page where I share my story and one of the last videos of my sweet mom before she died. It will give you a glimpse of what it’s like to lose the person who loves you most in the world to this devastating disease.
Here are the ways you can join me.
Register and you can walk with me and with my NBC4/Telemundo52 family. (BTW there is no registration fee or cost to participate)
or you can create your own team
or you can donate (any amount)
or you can just offer your support and love by sending this to your friends and family.😘
If you are walking on my team and would like a special pin that has been created for me and my mom, after you register please email me at Lynette.Romero@NBCUNI.com and I’ll let you know where you can meet us on walk day. Let’s take this journey together. 
🌻
Lynette

I’m willing to try all of the new Olympic sports are you?

Wow I’m never up past midnight but look at us out on a date night! Yes my hubby is feeling better. 🫶🏽 And to celebrate 8 weeks post surgery we went to dinner at Hollywood’s legendary @mussoandfrankgrill and then we went to the @hollywoodpantagestheatre to see @jacksonbrowne. He was great, putting on a 3 hour show. If you don’t know he’s considered by Rolling Stone to be one of “Greatest Songwriters of All Time.” It was a great time with classic rock and good vibes. Just what we needed. Swipe right for some of the highlights. And tomorrow we get to see our baby girl! A quick visit with our college kid just because we miss her. Hope you are spending your weekend making some good memories too. 🌻
